      Long-termism
   =20
 =20
One claim that you sometimes hear about financial markets is that they are =
excessively focused on the short term and systematically undervalue long-te=
rm investment. Public investors want good earnings and big stock buybacks=
=C2=A0this=C2=A0quarter, and get impatient when corporate managers spend mo=
ney on projects that will add lots of value in the long run but won=E2=80=
=99t pay off immediately. Great ideas don=E2=80=99t get funded if they can=
=E2=80=99t show results quickly. This concern strikes me as overstated =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0look at Tesla, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, sure, there is probably=
=C2=A0some truth=C2=A0to it.Another claim that you, uh, rarely hear about f=
inancial markets is that they are excessively focused on the long term and =
systematically undervalue short-term cash flows.=C2=A0Public investors want=
 a perpetual stream of growing earnings; if you offered them a company whos=
e business model was =E2=80=9Cmake a ton of cash for 10 years, pay it out t=
o shareholders in dividends, then vanish,=E2=80=9D they would turn up their=
 noses and put a very high discount rate on those cash flows. An entreprene=
ur with that business model would have a very hard time getting financing.A=
gain, I have rarely =E2=80=94 never? =E2=80=94=C2=A0heard anyone make that =
claim in precisely that form, and of course it isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really=C2=
=A0true, but again I think there is some truth to it. A well-known private-=
equity/vulture-capital/newspaper=C2=A0business model is to buy dying busine=
sses with good cash flows (for now), stop reinvesting in the business (beca=
use it=E2=80=99s dying), and harvest the cash flows while they last; the re=
ason this is a private-equity business model is that there is, for whatever=
 reason, some public-market inefficiency in funding those sorts of business=
es.[1]Incidentally these claims could both be true? Why not. Public markets=
 could place a high value on=C2=A0perpetuity, on being a company with good =
long-term prospects, but they could measure those prospects exclusively by =
quarterly growth trends because they don=E2=80=99t fully trust management t=
o plan for the long term.=C2=A0Yesterday Steve Schwarzman criticized enviro=
nmental investing=C2=A0at a Saudi investment conference, which is a very fu=
nny sentence to type but also kind of interesting:Steve Schwarzman, Blackst=
one=E2=80=99s billionaire co-founder, became the latest financier to sound =
the alarm about an energy crunch. (The most recent sign: U.S. oil prices hi=
t $85 a barrel this week, a seven-year high.) Speaking at the Future Invest=
ment Initiative conference in Saudi Arabia, he warned that an energy shorta=
ge could lead to =E2=80=9Creal unrest=E2=80=9D across the world =E2=80=94 a=
nd put forward a provocative culprit.A focus on E.S.G. is driving a credit =
crunch for oil and gas companies, Schwarzman and others say. So-called envi=
ronmental, social and corporate governance investing principles have spurre=
d investment giants to divest their holdings in oil and gas companies. That=
, according to Schwarzman, has made it hard for the industry to invest in n=
ew wells and other sources of capacity. =E2=80=9CIf you try and raise money=
 to drill holes, it=E2=80=99s almost impossible to get that money,=E2=80=9D=
 he said. (Blackstone has invested in both fossil-fuel and renewable energy=
 companies.) =E2=80=A6Even Larry Fink of BlackRock, who has been among the =
biggest advocates for Wall Street adopting E.S.G., is worried that outflows=
 from the fossil-fuel industry may be overdone. =E2=80=9CWe have these visi=
ons we could go from a brown world and we could wake up tomorrow there=E2=
=80=99d be a green world,=E2=80=9D he said at the F.I.I. conference. =E2=80=
=9CThat is not going to happen.=E2=80=9DOne way to tell that story is that,=
  influenced by Fink and others, investors now insist on long-term sustaina=
bility. They believe that a zero-carbon world is coming, they want to inves=
t in companies that will make money in a zero-carbon world, and they think =
that a lot of marginal oil drillers will not survive in that world. The oil=
 drillers might agree! =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re gonna drill for oil for 10 ye=
ars, sell it at $85 a barrel, make a lot of money for our investors, and th=
en close up shop when the world moves off oil=E2=80=9D is a perfectly reaso=
nable business plan. But =E2=80=94=C2=A0Schwarzman says =E2=80=94=C2=A0inve=
stors will not finance it anymore, because they are myopically obsessed wit=
h the long run.Actually there are two slightly different forms of the story=
. One is: =E2=80=9CThis is a good business model with positive expected val=
ue but investors, wrongly obsessed with the long run, won=E2=80=99t fund it=
.=E2=80=9D There the solution is simple: Steve Schwarzman, you run a multib=
illion-dollar asset manager,=C2=A0you=C2=A0fund it. You=E2=80=99ll make a l=
ot of money! Long-term-obsessed investors are systematically undervaluing t=
hese juicy short-term cash flows, and you can profit from their mistake by =
buying the cash flows cheap. This is actually sort of a  standard story of =
modern oil-and-gas investing: Big public companies are divesting from dirty=
 assets, and smaller private companies (and sovereigns) are buying those as=
sets at attractive rates of return. (Or, big public=C2=A0investors=C2=A0are=
 divesting from dirty oil-and-gas companies, and smaller, less ESG-constrai=
ned investors are funding them.)The other story would be: =E2=80=9CThis is =
a bad business model, because you have high upfront costs to drill oil well=
s, but instead of having a long time to pump oil and recover those costs, y=
ou only have a short time before oil is banned or whatever, so=C2=A0even no=
w=C2=A0a lot of new wells are no longer profitable, so of course investors =
don=E2=80=99t fund them.=E2=80=9D This is, uh, also kind of a standard stor=
y of modern oil-and-gas investing; there is quite a bit of history of drill=
ing in good times leading to bankruptcy when demand falls. Arguably if this=
 is the story then the solution is =E2=80=9Cthis is not a problem, just don=
=E2=80=99t fund unprofitable dirty things.=E2=80=9D But I suppose Schwarzma=
n could disagree. Perhaps drilling new wells is environmentally harmful, fi=
nancially unprofitable, but =E2=80=A6=C2=A0socially =E2=80=A6=C2=A0benefici=
al? Gotta pump oil unprofitably to keep people happy. Maybe governments sho=
uld subsidize oil drilling for a few years, then ban it?
