   =20
      Trump SPAC merger agreement
   =20
 =20
Last week, when Donald Trump announced that he had (1) formed a social medi=
a/streaming/cloud hosting/whatever company called Trump Media & Technology =
Group and (2) agreed to take it public by merging with a special purpose ac=
quisition company called=C2=A0Digital World Acquisition Corp., I  did a lit=
tle speculation about what would drive the stock price. Basically I figured=
 it will track, not how much money=C2=A0TMTG makes (it seems to have no pro=
duct), but rather how much attention is paid to Trump. =E2=80=9CMy guess is=
 that the stock will go up when Trump is on television,=E2=80=9D I wrote. =
=E2=80=9CMy guess is that each day that goes by without Trump news, the sto=
ck will go down a bit.=E2=80=9DCuriously, TMTG itself generated very little=
 news.=C2=A0This deal was announced by press release last Wednesday evening=
, and as of this Monday that was pretty much all that Trump=C2=A0or TMTG=C2=
=A0or DWAC had said about it. There is a silly investor presentation on TMT=
G=E2=80=99s website, which seems to predate the SPAC transaction and has no=
 real business information. I  wrote on Monday that=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m not sure I have ever seen a secretive SPAC merger announcement before.=
=E2=80=9D Shouldn=E2=80=99t they be telling people about this company that =
they=E2=80=99re trying to raise money for?But then yesterday some things ha=
ppened.=C2=A0Trump=C2=A0himself=C2=A0put out a =E2=80=A6=C2=A0thing? I gues=
s it is a press release though I can only find it hosted on=C2=A0weird webs=
ites; here are versions on Twitter and Reddit, and a New York Post summary.=
 It is titled =E2=80=9CStatement on TMTG by the 45th President Donald J. Tr=
ump=E2=80=9D and it says almost nothing at all about TMTG; it is four pages=
 of complaining about =E2=80=9Ccancel culture,=E2=80=9D etc. There is a lit=
tle bit of aspirational stuff about TMTG =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CUnlike wit=
h the Big Tech platforms, there will be no shadow-banning, throttling, demo=
nizing, or messing with algorithms for political manipulation,=E2=80=9D TMT=
G =E2=80=9Cwill also be launching an on-demand video streaming service that=
 competes with the increasingly =E2=80=98woke=E2=80=99 and politicized =E2=
=80=98entertainment=E2=80=99 programming created by Big Tech and Big Media =
players,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CTMTG also sees opportunities to create =E2=80=98=
cancel-proof=E2=80=99 alternatives in other key areas ranging from web serv=
ices to payment processing=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but there are no, you know, f=
acts. Who will run TMTG=E2=80=99s day-to-day operations? Have they hired a =
team of software engineers to build a new social network from scratch? Who =
have they signed to production deals for their new streaming service that w=
ill compete with Netflix? Who is leading the payment-processing initiative?=
 What will TMTG do with the $293 million it is raising from DWAC? What is t=
he monetization model for the social network? Why am I even typing all of t=
hese questions?Actually there is one fun fact in the press release, in the =
first sentence actually. =E2=80=9CLast week,=E2=80=9D Trump says, =E2=80=9C=
I announced the creation of a major new company.=E2=80=9D Ordinarily, there=
 are two distinct important events in the life of a SPAC company, generally=
 quite separate in time: One day the company is created, and then, probably=
 years later, it announces a SPAC merger. Here =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, it=E2=
=80=99s ambiguous, but doesn=E2=80=99t it seem like=C2=A0the company was cr=
eated to do the SPAC merger? It=E2=80=99s not that he started a company, fu=
nded it himself, got a team in place, figured out a business strategy, star=
ted developing the product, and eventually reached a point where he decided=
 to raise public capital, so last week he announced a SPAC deal. No, it=E2=
=80=99s that he started the company last week=C2=A0with the SPAC deal. I su=
spect that the $293 million of SPAC money will be the first funding this co=
mpany ever gets. That=E2=80=99s weird! Some companies go public via SPAC be=
fore their product is viable, but, you know, usually they=E2=80=99ve hired =
some engineers and, like, planned=C2=A0the product. Here I am not so sure. =
As Dan Primack put it last week, =E2=80=9CThis appears to be a shell compan=
y buying a shell company.=E2=80=9DAlso yesterday, DWAC =E2=80=94=C2=A0the S=
PAC that is taking TMTG public, which is itself already a public company =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0filed a Form 8-K summarizing and attaching the merger agreem=
ent for the deal. I was excited, but it is not particularly juicy. The merg=
er agreement is mostly standard=C2=A0boilerplate.[3] There is no disclosure=
 about the capital structure of TMTG or who owns it. There=C2=A0is=C2=A0som=
e new disclosure of the =E2=80=9Cearnout,=E2=80=9D in which Trump and his f=
ellow TMTG shareholders get extra shares if the company=E2=80=99s stock pri=
ce stays high. The basic deal is that Trump and friends get about 86 millio=
n shares of the combined company, while DWAC=E2=80=99s public shareholders =
get about 29 million and its sponsors get another 7 million.[4] The earnout=
 gives Trump and friends an extra 40 million shares if the stock is above $=
30 consistently after the deal closes.[5] Assuming that it will be =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0it has never closed below $45 since the deal was announced =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Trump will have about 126 million shares worth, at yesterday=E2=80=
=99s closing price of $59.07, about $7.4 billion.=C2=A0Meanwhile the SPAC s=
ponsors are also doing well:The obscure financiers who launched the shell c=
ompany that is taking former President Donald Trump=E2=80=99s social-media =
venture public are poised for a big payday if the deal gets completed.The t=
otal windfall would stand at about $400 million at the stock=E2=80=99s curr=
ent price, after shares skyrocketed sixfold following the deal=E2=80=99s an=
nouncement.Both Trump and the SPAC sponsors will be locked up for a while a=
fter the deal closes, though, so they can=E2=80=99t just sell all their sto=
ck and walk away. Not immediately I mean.
