   =20
      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20
Will Facebook Inc. get in trouble with the Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on for, uh, making its users sad in order to maximize profits for sharehold=
ers? My gut is that the answer is no, but I do always say that everything i=
s securities fraud,=C2=A0and Facebook certainly did some things, so I can=
=E2=80=99t rule it out. Anyway:Now one of the most pressing questions is wh=
ether the Securities and Exchange Commission =E2=80=94 the federal agency w=
here Ms. Haugen sent the documents =E2=80=94 will significantly add to the =
company=E2=80=99s woes.Whistle-blowers have filed at least nine complaints =
to the agency, which has oversight of public companies like Facebook, using=
 a selection of the internal documents to argue that Facebook misled invest=
ors with a rosier picture of the company than they knew to be true. The S.E=
.C. can impose big fines for misleading investors and impose restrictions o=
n corporate leaders.A case from securities regulators is probably far from =
a slam dunk, several legal experts said. The accusations in the complaints =
don=E2=80=99t appear to be quite as clear-cut as many other accounting and =
fraud cases taken up by the agency, they said.The S.E.C. declined to say wh=
ether it had opened an investigation. Even such a move could be problematic=
 for Facebook, leading to depositions of top executives and forcing the com=
pany to share private communications and other business documents.My unders=
tanding is that Facebook critics file SEC whistle-blower complaints mostly =
because that gives them certain statutory protections against retaliation; =
Facebook can more vigorously go after a =E2=80=9Cleaker=E2=80=9D than it ca=
n an =E2=80=9CSEC whistle-blower.=E2=80=9D They are not really=C2=A0that=C2=
=A0concerned with Facebook=E2=80=99s shareholders (they=E2=80=99re concerne=
d with Facebook=E2=80=99s users, civil society, etc.), but for practical re=
asons the SEC is a good place to file a complaint.=C2=A0And my guess is tha=
t this sort of thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0not accounting fraud, but various sorts=
 of debatable nefariousness that was not publicly disclosed and that, when =
it came out, made the stock go down =E2=80=94=C2=A0is the kind of =E2=80=9C=
securities fraud=E2=80=9D that plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers love but that th=
e SEC stays away from. In its enforcement action the SEC prefers to go afte=
r=C2=A0actual=C2=A0fraud on shareholders, things that endanger the integrit=
y of public markets, not miscellaneous unpleasantness that correlates with =
a stock drop. Not always though? Facebook is a big exciting target. =E2=80=
=9CFederal Trade Commission Scrutinizing Facebook Disclosures,=E2=80=9D the=
 Wall Street Journal reports. Maybe the SEC =E2=80=94=C2=A0the U.S.  meta-r=
egulator, with jurisdiction over everything any public company does =E2=80=
=94 will want to get in on the action?
