<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Long-termism</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One claim that you sometimes hear abou=
t financial markets is that they are excessively focused on the short term =
and systematically undervalue long-term investment. Public investors want g=
ood earnings and big stock buybacks=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>quarter, and ge=
t impatient when corporate managers spend money on projects that will add l=
ots of value in the long run but won=E2=80=99t pay off immediately. Great i=
deas don=E2=80=99t get funded if they can=E2=80=99t show results quickly. T=
his concern strikes me as overstated =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25484834.267686/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMjYvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWhhZC1hLWdvb2Qt=
ZGF5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjcyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJ=
jZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTAyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB697449ed" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">look at Tesla</a>, etc. =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but, sure, there is probably=C2=A0some truth=C2=A0to it.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another claim that you, uh, rarely hear about financia=
l markets is that they are excessively focused on the long term and systema=
tically undervalue short-term cash flows.=C2=A0Public investors want a perp=
etual stream of growing earnings; if you offered them a company whose busin=
ess model was =E2=80=9Cmake a ton of cash for 10 years, pay it out to share=
holders in dividends, then vanish,=E2=80=9D they would turn up their noses =
and put a very high discount rate on those cash flows. An entrepreneur with=
 that business model would have a very hard time getting financing.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, I have rarely =E2=80=94 never? =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0heard anyone make that claim in precisely that form, and of course it is=
n=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>true, but again I think there is <em>=
some </em>truth to it. A well-known private-equity/vulture-capital/<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25484834.267686/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL21hZ2F6aW5lL2FyY2hpdmUvMjAyMS8xMS9hbGRlbi1nbG9i=
YWwtY2FwaXRhbC1raWxsaW5nLWFtZXJpY2FzLW5ld3NwYXBlcnMvNjIwMTcxLw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cBa345aac7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">newspaper</a>=C2=A0business model is to buy =
dying businesses with good cash flows (for now), stop reinvesting in the bu=
siness (because it=E2=80=99s dying), and harvest the cash flows while they =
last; the reason this is a private-equity business model is that there is, =
for whatever reason, some public-market inefficiency in funding those sorts=
 of businesses.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally these claim=
s could both be true? Why not. Public markets could place a high value on=
=C2=A0<em>perpetuity</em>, on being a company with good long-term prospects=
, but they could measure those prospects exclusively by quarterly growth tr=
ends because they don=E2=80=99t fully trust management to plan for the long=
 term.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yesterday <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25484834.267686/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW=
1lcy5jb20vMjAyMS8xMC8yNy9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9zY2h3YXJ6bWFuLWVuZXJneS1jc=
nVuY2guaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB62673829" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Steve Schwarzman c=
riticized environmental investing</a>=C2=A0at a Saudi investment conference=
, which is a very funny sentence to type but also kind of interesting:</p><=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Steve Schwarzman, Blackstone=E2=80=
=99s billionaire co-founder, became the latest financier to sound the alarm=
 about an energy crunch. (The most recent sign: U.S. oil prices hit $85 a b=
arrel this week, a seven-year high.) Speaking at the Future Investment Init=
iative conference in Saudi Arabia, he warned that an energy shortage could =
lead to =E2=80=9Creal unrest=E2=80=9D across the world =E2=80=94 and put fo=
rward a provocative culprit.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A focus on E.S=
.G. is driving a credit crunch for oil and gas companies, Schwarzman and ot=
hers say. So-called environmental, social and corporate governance investin=
g principles have spurred investment giants to divest their holdings in oil=
 and gas companies. That, according to Schwarzman, has made it hard for the=
 industry to invest in new wells and other sources of capacity. =E2=80=9CIf=
 you try and raise money to drill holes, it=E2=80=99s almost impossible to =
get that money,=E2=80=9D he said. (Blackstone has invested in both fossil-f=
uel and renewable energy companies.) =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Even Larry Fink of BlackRock, who has been among the biggest advocates =
for Wall Street adopting E.S.G., is worried that outflows from the fossil-f=
uel industry may be overdone. =E2=80=9CWe have these visions we could go fr=
om a brown world and we could wake up tomorrow there=E2=80=99d be a green w=
orld,=E2=80=9D he said at the F.I.I. conference. =E2=80=9CThat is not going=
 to happen.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way t=
o tell that story is that, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/25484834.267686/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEtMTQvYmxhY2tyb2NrLWhhcy1ncmVlbi1wbGFucz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI3M=
jFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1f=
dGVybT0yMTEwMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf4=
258210" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> influenced by Fink</a> and others, investors now insist on=
 long-term sustainability. They believe that a zero-carbon world is coming,=
 they want to invest in companies that will make money in a zero-carbon wor=
ld, and they think that a lot of marginal oil drillers will not survive in =
that world. The oil drillers might agree! =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re gonna dril=
l for oil for 10 years, sell it at $85 a barrel, make a lot of money for ou=
r investors, and then close up shop when the world moves off oil=E2=80=9D i=
s a perfectly reasonable business plan. But =E2=80=94=C2=A0Schwarzman says =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0investors will not finance it anymore, because they are myop=
ically obsessed with the long run.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Actually=
 there are two slightly different forms of the story. One is: =E2=80=9CThis=
 is a good business model with positive expected value but investors, wrong=
ly obsessed with the long run, won=E2=80=99t fund it.=E2=80=9D There the so=
lution is simple: Steve Schwarzman, you run a multibillion-dollar asset man=
ager,=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>fund it. You=E2=80=99ll make a lot of money! L=
ong-term-obsessed investors are systematically undervaluing these juicy sho=
rt-term cash flows, and you can profit from their mistake by buying the cas=
h flows cheap. This is actually sort of a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/25484834.267686/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDgvc29tZW9uZS1pcy1nb2luZy10by1kcmlsbC10aG=
Utb2lsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMjcyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nvd=
XJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTAyNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB337f4534" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> standard story</a> of modern oil=
-and-gas investing: Big public companies are divesting from dirty assets, a=
nd smaller private companies (and sovereigns) are buying those assets at at=
tractive rates of return. (Or, big public=C2=A0<em>investors=C2=A0</em>are =
divesting from dirty oil-and-gas companies, and smaller, less ESG-constrain=
ed investors are funding them.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other s=
tory would be: =E2=80=9CThis is a bad business model, because you have high=
 upfront costs to drill oil wells, but instead of having a long time to pum=
p oil and recover those costs, you only have a short time before oil is ban=
ned or whatever, so=C2=A0<em>even now</em>=C2=A0a lot of new wells are no l=
onger profitable, so of course investors don=E2=80=99t fund them.=E2=80=9D =
This is, uh, also kind of a standard story of modern oil-and-gas investing;=
 there is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25484834=
.267686/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyMC8wNy8xMi9jbGltYXRlL29pbC1mcmF=
ja2luZy1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LW1ldGhhbmUtZXhlY3V0aXZlLXBheS5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB0ca542d8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">quite a bit of history</a> of drilling in good ti=
mes leading to bankruptcy when demand falls. Arguably if this is the story =
then the solution is =E2=80=9Cthis is not a problem, just don=E2=80=99t fun=
d unprofitable dirty things.=E2=80=9D But I suppose Schwarzman could disagr=
ee. Perhaps drilling new wells is environmentally harmful, financially unpr=
ofitable, but =E2=80=A6=C2=A0socially =E2=80=A6=C2=A0beneficial? Gotta pump=
 oil unprofitably to keep people happy. Maybe governments should subsidize =
oil drilling for a few years, then ban it?</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sp=
